Rating: 3
This is a very yummy, hearty soup. My final product was great but like others I made a few subtle changes to the recipe...I dissolved 2 Knorr beef boullion cubes for my broth but only used 3cups of water. I added 1 small can of diced tomatoes with all its liquid. I then used 2c cabbage, 2-4inch beets, 1 potato, 1 carrot and 1 parsnip all chopped. For seasoning I added 1 large minced clove of garlic and a 1/2 tsp or so each of fresh cracked salt & pepper. Then I added one huge TBone steak bone from my freezer and simmered it slowly for about 1hour. I did not puree any of it - I prefer the rustic look...the potato melted into the soup and seemed to thicken it up quite nicely...at the end I added 1tbsp of butter and a squish of fresh lemon. Hot or cold this was a wonderfully rich soup - I served it with a dollup of sour cream and parsley sprig for color (cause its the only herb still alive in my garden right now) I will definately be making this one again & again!

Rating: 4
This is a great soup as written, but I think even more delicious with some changes/additions. The first time I made it I had fresh beets with tops, so I chopped the beet tops and added to the other ingredients - I have since subbed with fresh spinach. Also added 3 large carrots diced, some garlic powder and a dash or two of ground cloves. For liquid I used 6 cups vegetable broth and the liquid from the canned tomatoes. But the real key to outstanding flavour is fresh dill - a generous handful of fresh minced dill added during the last 10 minutes of cooking, and additional dill and finely grated lemon zest sprinkled on the sour cream just before serving. If you use dill, delete the parsley. Also, use the juice from 1 whole lemon - I have found the acid counteracts any over sweetness and adds another layer of flavour. So fresh tasting, so yummy, and other than the sour cream so very healthy. A lovely soup and a great change from the good old standby soups we seem to make over and again. Please try it, I'm sure you will be delighted. A definite keeper!

